All you really need to know right now is that Arianne and Adam are twins. The rest is in the story.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>PROLOGUE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
“Arianne, Adam, listen to me. Listen! I love you. But this is the work I have to do. It will be the work you will carry on. Tell your mother…tell her I’m alright. Give her my love. Melody, too. You’re going to have to take care of each other now, and you’ll be okay. You’ve got twice the power I have. Kids, the hardest thing in this world is to live in it. It’s not being who you are. It’s not shouldering the world. It’s just…living. Be brave. Live. For me.”<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>CHAPTERone<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;&gt;arianne</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
“Ari! You ready?”<br>
“Yeah, let’s go before I change my mind.”<br>
I grabbed my bag and together Adam and I walked outside.<br>
“Ahh! It’s cold!”<br>
“It’s  winter, is what it is. What did you expect?”<br>
“Something a little more…warm?”<br>
I sighed. My brother was such a dick sometimes.<br>
“It’s also night. Anyway. Did you bring my crossbow from Sophie’s?”<br>
“Yeah. She fixed it into a double.”<br>
“Cool.”<br>
“Are you going now?”<br>
Mum was framed by the light from the hall.<br>
“Yeah, we’ll be back later. Don’t wait up.”<br>
She nodded, and I made out the vague shape of Melody.<br>
“When do I get to patrol?” she pouted.<br>
“Not until you are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->” we all yelled back. I didn’t hear her complaints as the door shut softly closed.<br>
“So, are we looking for anything in particular tonight?” Adam asked as we wandered down the street.<br>
“Nah. Least, I’m not picking up anything. You?”<br>
He stopped and looked around him. Finally he shook his head.<br>
“Guess we should probably just walk round til we find something to maim or kill.”<br>
We’re not crazy psycho twins. Really. And we’re not Slayers, like my friend Sophie assumed the day we told her about our family history.<br>
We’re the SpellBound, me and Adam. And our dad, before us. It stretches way back, this line.<br>
“I vote for kill. I don’t like maiming. Too…messy.”<br>
“Aww, too weak to handle the gore?”<br>
“Please. I was the one who sliced the head of the Koravokian demon last week after you ran away.”<br>
“Excuse me? His brother was in the corner and he was about to kick your sorry butt!”<br>
I half-heartedly punched him.<br>
“Your crossbow isn’t gonna be a lot of good without these.”<br>
He handed me a packet of bolts and I slid a couple into place.<br>
“Thanks.”<br>
“No worries. Just saving your sorry butt.”<br>
“Oh, shut – do you hear that?”<br>
Adam stiffened. <br>
“Yeah,” he whispered. “What do you think it is?”<br>
I pulled my finger across my throat to shut him up, then pointed to a nearby bush, the apparent source of suspect rustling. We split, sneaking towards it from different directions. Adam had a small double-headed ax at the ready. <br>
I pried the bushes apart with my crossbow. <br>
“Dammit, Tycho! What are you doing?”<br>
“What does it look like?” The half-demon replied grumpily. “I’m <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>eating.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->”<br>
“Ugh. Not down our street you’re not.”<br>
Adam grabbed the dirty creature by the scruff of his baggy neck.<br>
“Come back here again, you’ll be missing your head. Go.”<br>
Tycho brushed himself off.<br>
“A beast has gotta eat, you know!”<br>
“I’m sorry, you’re confusing me with someone who gives a damn. Get out of here, Tycho!”<br>
He scampered.<br>
“Should we put up a ward against him?”<br>
Surprised, Adam turned to face me.<br>
“Last time we tried putting up a ward, we blew up Fred.”<br>
“Oh, yeah. Do you think Mel’s ever going to notice that fish isn’t Fred?”<br>
“Hell, no.”<br>
“Good.”<br>
“Well, do you want to move?”<br>
We started walking again.<br>
“Do you ever wish all bad guys were like Tycho?”<br>
“All bad guys are like Tycho. All they want is to eat, sleep, and kill merry.”<br>
“Yeah, but Tycho doesn’t want to kill us.”<br>
He shrugged. “I’m not concerned. Gives me something to do.”<br>
“What if-&quot;<br>
“We’ve been doing this long enough to not worry about the what if’s,” he broke in sharply.<br>
“I guess you’re right…”<br>
I stared up into the sky. It was a cloudy night, so I couldn’t even see the moon.<br>
“You’re worried about Hogwarts.”<br>
“You’re quick,” I replied.<br>
“But why are you worried about it? No place is safer than Hogwarts.”<br>
“It’s not the safe thing…it’s just I want to get back there. I hate that we had to quit because of the stupid bound stuff. Seriously, fight until you die? Who made up that stupid rule?”<br>
“I believe that would be our family. And we’ll get back to Hogwarts one day. Admit it, you like being at normal school.”<br>
“I like having my non magic friends around, but it gets a little monotonous. Sometimes I just want to show off and turn a rat yellow.”<br>
Adam snorted. “As you do. Come on, we’ll go hit the bad part of town.”<br>
“Hurray, a whole two blocks to walk!”<br>
“You’re never going to stop mocking the small town thing are you?”<br>
“I’m sorry, but no.”<br>
We were the only idiots out, so we had to keep pretty quiet as we walked the streets. <br>
“This is pointless,” I whinged. “There’s nothing here.”<br>
“Exactly. What’s not here, will be somewhere else. We have to keep going.”<br>
“I’m making Mum give us a curfew.”<br>
He checked his watch. “Look, right now, it’s twelve. We’ll stay out for another couple of hours then we’ll go home.”<br>
“If it’s really quiet I’m going home in one.”<br>
“Okay.”<br>
About three seconds after I said this, I heard a scream. Adam grinned and I couldn’t help but smile back. We were <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>made</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for this hero thing. We raced in the direction of the scream.<br>
“I hate alleys. I think they should be banned.”<br>
“Oh, gross. Vampire.”<br>
“Well, chuck us your crossbow.”<br>
I did so, and hung back holding Adam’s ax. He rushed in.<br>
There was a guy there, maybe in his late twenties, looking like he was about to shit himself, with a woman bent over his neck, teeth bared. <br>
“Slayer!”<br>
I groaned before I could stop it. “When are you people going to learn that we’re not Slayers? For God’s sake!”<br>
Adam grabbed the man’s arm and spun him away, into me. I caught him easily.<br>
“Hey, that’s <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>your</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cue to run.” I gave him a little push and he took off. Adam, meanwhile, had easily dusted the woman using my crossbow. I yanked it from his hands.<br>
“Those things are no good at close range.”<br>
“So you should have used your ax. It’s not my problem.”<br>
Adam hoisted his bag over his shoulder.<br>
“Can we call it quits now?” I asked. He nodded. The walk home was long, slow, and boring.<br>
“You know, that’s the first vampire there’s been for a few weeks.”<br>
“And Tycho and the Koravokians were the first demons in ages too,” Adam said slowly.<br>
“Do you think…do you think maybe the flow’s slowing?”<br>
We slowed to a stop, contemplating what it could mean.<br>
“We could have a break,” Adam ventured.<br>
“We could go back to Hogwarts.”<br>
“Let’s not get too far ahead of ourselves.”<br>
“Too late. I’m up at life after Hogwarts, evil – free.”<br>
“Or in the least, evil – lite.” He tugged my hand. “Feet firmly on the ground, eh?”<br>
I hadn’t even realised I’d been levitating. I came back to Earth, but my head was still in the clouds, dreaming of a better time. Adam had to nudge me when we got home so I didn’t bang into the front door.<br>
“Arianne? Is that you?”<br>
“We’re home, Mum!”<br>
“Shush! Melody’s asleep.”<br>
“We’re home, Mum,” Adam whispered, being a dick, as usual. <br>
“How was it?”<br>
“Eerily quiet,” I said, throwing my stuff onto a chair. “We’re thinking of taking a break.”<br>
Her eyes lit up, tired though they were.<br>
“That’s brilliant. Is it really quiet then?”<br>
Adam and I nodded.<br>
“So what will you do?”<br>
We flopped onto the couch.<br>
“Dunno,” Adam said. “Bum round here for awhile.”<br>
“Maybe go back to Hogwarts.”<br>
One thing about Adam and I: we may be twins, and we may be bound together, but that’s where the similarities end. Going back to Hogwarts for our last three years is my dream; playing soccer for England is his. I suppose I want the magical side of things, while Adam’s pining to be normal. <br>
“There’s no rush,” Mum murmured. “You should rest while you can. While the floods have rolled back.”<br>
“I’m gonna be a fireman,” Adam quoted swiftly. I laughed. It was from a song we’d heard Dad sing tonnes of times to Melody. I’m gonna be a fireman, when the floods roll back…the tune rolled into my head like a wave, bringing back crashing memories of Dad. I forced them away, locked them in a safe part of my mind, far from my own prying inner eye.<br>
“Off to bed, then,” Mum said briskly. “And pick up your things, I don’t want Melody finding them in the morning.”<br>
“She might shoot another hole in the wall,” Adam snickered. He grabbed his things and set off upstairs. <br>
“Ari? You ought to go to bed, love. You’ve got school tomorrow.”<br>
“Mmm…”<br>
“What’s wrong?”<br>
“Oh, nothing much…just…if I went back to Hogwarts, I don’t think Adam would come with me.”<br>
She looked taken aback. “What makes you say that?”<br>
“I don’t know. Just a feeling, I guess.”<br>
“I can’t speak for Adam, but I think he’ll stick by you, Arianne.”<br>
“You’re probably right. Night.”<br>
“Good night, love. I’m gonna be a fireman, when the floods roll back, you just wait and see, this ain’t my last attack…”<br>
I carried the tune in my head as I drifted off to sleep.<br>
