“Mum! We’re leaving!”<br>
“Alright, be home by dinner. Are you taking any weapons with you?”<br>
“Just our wands.”<br>
“In the hands of Adam, that is one dangerous weapon,” Sophie remarked. She’d come to watch us go. For some reason she finds Floo powder interesting. I just find it sickening.<br>
“See you later, Soph. Could you try and find out about Cality?”<br>
“On it. I’ll fix you up a mace while I’m at it.”<br>
“Our lives are different from other people’s,” Adam said, shaking his head.<br>
“A mace?”<br>
“Yeah…I’ll try, anyway. I saw some instructions.”<br>
“’Kay. See ya.”<br>
“Bye.”<br>
Adam went first. I followed a few seconds later.<br>
We landed in the seer’s office.<br>
“Haven’t been here for ages,” Adam whispered, “and it’s still dusty as hell.”<br>
“Can I help you two? Oh, dear, no, don’t touch that!”<br>
I withdrew my hand quickly from the crystal I’d been about to pick up.<br>
“You’ll disturb it’s flow, there’s a dear. Now, can I help you?”<br>
The seer we’d come was stereotypical. Leathered skin, wild hair, and piercing green eyes. We’d been to see one before, but most go mad. The visions get to them mentally. Few do it professionally.<br>
“We need to find out something.”<br>
“Well, you’ve come to the right place!” he twittered. “What can I tell you?”<br>
“We need to know if it’s the right time to leave home yet.”<br>
Adam and I know well enough not to give away too much.<br>
“Ah, you want to go back to Hogwarts, yes? Give me a hand each.”<br>
We did as he asked and he squeezed his eyes shut. Adam looked at me doubtfully. The man snapped an eye open.<br>
“All doubtful thougts at the doormat, please.”<br>
He closed it again and started humming loudly.<br>
“Yes, I see…your mother and sister, you are very worried about them? Don’t be. They are strong. But don’t let them separate yet. The results may be disastrous.”<br>
“Melody’s-&quot;<br>
“Eight, I am aware. But still. It is just a warning. Now, the real question at hand. Leaving soon would bring about calamity-&quot;<br>
“So we can’t go?!”<br>
“I said <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>soon</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. If you are going to leave for Hogwarts, now is the time.”<br>
“Will anything happen to  -&quot;<br>
“No. No, your family and friends will be fine. In fact they are safer without you here attracting all manners of nasty.”<br>
“So we’ll be alright to go. We can leave?”<br>
“You can.”<br>
“Thank you,” I said happily. “Thanks a lot.”<br>
“Au revoir, children! See you in France!” <br>
Adam pushed the door open for me and I walked straight into a warm pool of sunshine. I lifted my face to it, feeling it for the first time in awhile.<br>
“You okay?”<br>
“I’m fine.”<br>
“You look…pale.”<br>
“I’m…” I put a hand to my head. “Sorry, I just…I just have a bit of a headache.”<br>
“You said you were –&quot;<br>
“Adam, drop it!”<br>
“Alright, alright. Calm down.”<br>
“Sorry. Feel a bit shocked I suppose. I mean…we’re finally going back, Adam. We’re finally going back!”<br>
“In time for the start of term in a couple of days, too.”<br>
“God, we’re going to have so much to do.”<br>
“Yeah, but it’s not new. We could be going to an entirely new place. It’s Hogwarts.”<br>
“You know what’s sad? It’s not just Hogwarts. It’s home.”<br>
“Is it because of Dad?”<br>
“In a way. Since…since then it’s felt like the place where he’s still there, you know? He’s still, there’s a part of him, it’s still there. I want to get back there so bad.”<br>
“Know how you feel. Well, sort of. I’m not in love with-&quot;<br>
“Stop right there!”<br>
“Speak of the devil…”<br>
Adam ducked off and I spun around.<br>
Straight into <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>him</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
I rattled off a string of silent colourful swear words.<br>
“Arianne!”<br>
“Hey.”<br>
I shoved my hands into my pockets. <br>
“Hogwarts shopping, I presume?”<br>
“Uh, yeah. That’s it.”<br>
“You’ve been missed.”<br>
“Thanks, I think.”<br>
“See you round.”<br>
“Yeah. Around. Bye.”<br>
He walked off. As he did so he paused and turned around, giving me a half – hearted wave and smile. Well. Smirk. Don’t know if the boy can smile.<br>
So I’m not particularly sure why I like him. I know why Adam likes Sophie, other than the fact she’s a total bombshell and smart to boot. She knows about us – everything about us. There’s no need to hide anything from her. And that’s great, that’s wonderful; that feeling of no secrecy. For me it’s the same with him. He knows about me and Adam, the job we have to do, the job we might die doing, and he doesn’t try to distance himself from me. You know, preparing for the time I don’t come back from patrol or a big fight. Like I’ve felt from other people at Hogwarts. Friends I’ve made, who I’ve told, they start to stay away from me. Chain reaction, they tell others to do the same. Don’t go near those two. Okay, it hurts. But it doesn’t matter so much anymore. If anything it makes it easier on us.<br>
“Thinking deep thoughts?”<br>
I jumped, startled by Adam. “I’m not kidding, you have to stop doing that. You’ll kill me one day.”<br>
“Whatever. You wanna go back?”<br>
“We’ve still got time…”<br>
“There’s nothing here. We’ll have to come back tomorrow, anyway.”<br>
“Yeah, you’re right. ’Kay. Let’s go.”<br>
When we got home, Sophie was waiting on the couch with a grim look on her face.<br>
“I don’t like that look,” Adam told her.<br>
“You won’t like what I have to say. I spent some time researching Cality, then I went back to cracking the text. It’s bad.”<br>
“Apocalypse-y bad or average bad?”<br>
“The first.”<br>
“Crap.”<br>
“Cality or text first?”<br>
“Cality.”<br>
“Okay. Cality is some big kind of war demon. Sort of a death – bringer, you know? All for war and darkness, pain as bright as steel, you know the drill. Anyway. He’s thinking, hey, Reaver time’s come round again, let’s throw a big demon-y party. Pin the ax on the innocent, that type of thing. The ugly that showed up here was one of his followers, trying to take you out. Bit of a wimpy one, really. But there’ll be more. Cality’s objective is probably to take you out of the picture, leaving him free to get down with general evil. Including the Reaver.”<br>
She inhaled deeply. <br>
“The text, now the text could be helpful. It’s a prophecy, but it’s a lot more. Most of the stuff in it has happened more than once. The rising of the Reaver, for one. That’s something that’s been going on for donkey’s years. So far what I’ve got is you have the power to do what no other Spellbound have been able to do before: beat the Reaver. It hasn’t been done by any other bound. Whether that’s because of your doubled power or just because you’re stronger, I don’t know. We’ll find out.”<br>
“Reaver…that’s…big.”<br>
“Bigger than big,” Sophie nodded. “Enormous.”<br>
“But it means we can’t leave, doesn’t it?” I asked, feeling my heart sink. <br>
“<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>En contrare</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, my witchy friend. Locator spell performed by you two and you’re off to wherever the little Reaver lies. Could be anywhere. Last Reaver was Asian.”<br>
“Mei Keang. I’ve read about her.”<br>
“Well, yeah. The Reaver gang are widespread throughout the world. On top of this, it would be safer for your family if you were to leave. That magnet I told you about? The power’s been kicked up. All manners of bad will be on their way.”<br>
“You’ve been busy,” Adam said, admiration in his tone. Sophie grinned.<br>
“Yeah, well. Took a few breaks, wandered down to the shop…”<br>
She pulled something out of her bag.<br>
“Oh, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>cool.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->”<br>
I pulled a wickedly sharp athame with an ornately carved handle. <br>
“Pretty, isn’t it?” Sophie said, barely keeping the pride out of her voice. “Got a few powers on it too, I’m told. Should help you a lot.”<br>
“Or hinder the fighting. Knives aren’t too much with the grace, Soph.”<br>
“You’ll get it. More training with hand – to – hand combat, then throw in the knife. Handy for stabbing.”<br>
“And sticking.”<br>
“You frighten me, Arianne.”<br>
“Oh, Adam, you should be used to it. Sophie, are you staying for tea?”<br>
Mum had come back in, catching us unawares.<br>
“If that’s okay?”<br>
“Of course, love. You’re helping my children, aren’t you? Least I can do is cook you a meal.”<br>
“Thanks.”<br>
Mum walked away again.<br>
“So, this Reaver? Got any details on her?”<br>
“Nah. But the locator should help a lot.”<br>
“Great. After dinner.”<br>
“Wouldn’t have it any other way.”<br>
