After dinner the three of us headed to Sophie’s. Patrol would be missed tonight, Arianne and I had decided. The Reaver…that was bigger than anything we’d have faced. <br>
“Well, well. There are two. I thought you were myths.”<br>
“You were myth – taken,” Arianne grinned at the two standing before us. One was your run-of-the-mill vamp, the other was a demon we knew – Drike.<br>
“So, someone wanna be chuckin’ me a weapon?”  <br>
“Just get behind us, Soph.”<br>
She did, but I knew inside she was aching to fight. But Arianne was only carrying a stake. I’d been stupid and not bothered. However, a good fighter knows how to improvise. <br>
Alternatively they can fight without weapons. <br>
“Arianne, you take the vampire.”<br>
“No sweat.”<br>
“Sophie, tree!”<br>
She snapped a low branch off a nearby tree and threw it to me. It might not dust the demon, but it’d hurt.<br>
“C’mere, you little bastard. I said I was gonna kill you, today’s the day.”<br>
I started towards him, but he moved easily past me, near Sophie. She assumed a fighting stance, and he didn’t hesitate. He brought his foot up and around, heading for her head. She ducked, but came up fast to grab his foot. Using his momentum against him she twirled it round and he spun out of control – right for me. I had the branch ready and drove it home into his chest. He screamed. That was enough to distract his friend, and Arianne wedged the stake into his chest. His dust scattered into the wind.<br>
“Drike. Huh. Go, Adam.”<br>
“Thanks.”<br>
Drike pulled the branch from himself, staring at the gaping wound left. He swore as he tossed it aside. <br>
“Asshole!”<br>
“You’ll live, sadly. Arianne…”<br>
“On it.” She whirled behind him and snatched his arms, pinning them behind his back.<br>
“Okay, Drike. Here’s the deal. You’re not strolling randomly down our street for the sake of looking at the stars. What do you want?”<br>
“Get stuffed, Slayer.”<br>
“My God! Adam, kill him! Kill him now!”<br>
“What…is…it…going…to…take…for…you to learn we’re not Slayers!”<br>
I kicked him with each word. He was starting to flop around a bit.<br>
“Not so strong.”<br>
“Adam, quit playing.”<br>
“Got nothing to kill him with!”<br>
“Are you an idiot? Just…you know…branch?!”<br>
Something I’ve learned. Nothing, just about nothing, survives a piece of wood through the heart. So I shoved that branch through so hard it protruded out the other side. Sophie made a noise of disgust as she stepped over Drike’s body.<br>
“What are we going to do with him?” Arianne asked. “We can’t just leave him here.”<br>
“I think his self-cleaning mechanism just kicked in. Look!”<br>
Sophie pointed at his body, which was slowly fading away.<br>
“Cool. So, onwards?”<br>
“And upwards.”<br>
We continued walking. No one was home at Sophie’s. She took us to her room and switched on her computer.<br>
“You’ve got the stuff, right?”<br>
Arianne shook a little package in her hand. “’Course.” <br>
“Okay, you guys do that in the hall, and I’m going to work on your text a bit more.”<br>
“Sounds like a plan.”<br>
Arianne and I went into the hall and sat down. She set out the stuff and when she was finished we joined hands and began to chant over a world map. It’s sort of advanced scrying.<br>
“Adam, look…”<br>
A tiny section of the map was glowing.<br>
“Sophie! We found her!”<br>
“Great, where?”<br>
“France!”<br>
“Crap!”<br>
“What?”<br>
“Last known whereabouts of Cality!”<br>
We cleared up and went into her room, crowding around her.<br>
“Cality, early 1700s to present, has been sighted in various places, most notably America and England. The last sighting was in France.”<br>
“Is that it?”<br>
“Pretty much. But he’s not going to be your biggest worry.”<br>
“The Reaver?”<br>
“Oh, yeah. Guys…I don’t want to say it. But the Reaver is the biggest piece of evil to walk the earth. There’s a reason they only come around once every hundred years or so.”<br>
“You’re saying there’s a very good chance we’ll die.”<br>
“Yeah.”<br>
“We can handle it,” Arianne said uncertainly. “We’ve got the best chance, right?”<br>
Sophie nodded. “But Arianne-&quot;<br>
“But nothing,” I broke in. “We go to France. We find her. We kill her. World safe for a little while longer.”<br>
“Adam, you’re leaping before you look. Reaver groove is powerful.”<br>
“So are we!”<br>
“Not as powerful as her!”<br>
I knew she was right, but I couldn’t let it go. I wasn’t going to die.<br>
“We have to train. If we’re going to beat her, we have to be stronger.”<br>
Arianne was more accepting of everything than me. <br>
“Come on, Adam. We should go home. Get started.”<br>
“I’ll meet you.”<br>
“Adam-&quot;<br>
“I said I’ll meet you!”<br>
She left. I sat across from Sophie. She wouldn’t look at me.<br>
“Sophie.”<br>
“What?”<br>
“Look at me.”<br>
She did so, reluctantly.<br>
“Just…if anything does happen. You know Ari and I, we love you, okay?”<br>
She looked surprised. Well, I guess it’s not often I have displays of emotion like this.<br>
“I know, Adam.”<br>
I struggled to find something more to say. She twirled her hair, and I was caught up in that movement, watching her. <br>
I shook my head to clear it and went to find Arianne.<br>
“What did you tell her?”<br>
“Nothing.”<br>
At home we sparred for hours, long into the night, using all kinds of stuff. Mum came down once to check on us, then left. Ari stopped to watch her go, narrowly dodging my hand. She sat on the ground, staring at the door.<br>
“Are you scared, Adam?”<br>
“Yes.”<br>
“Good. Me too. Scared for us or scared for everyone else?”<br>
“Both.”<br>
“Same. I think…if we die, Mum and Melody will be safer, won’t they?”<br>
“I don’t know, Ari. Maybe.”<br>
“But if we do the power could pass onto Melody. I don’t want her to have this.”<br>
“So we’ll live. We’ll fight and we’ll win.”<br>
Mum burst back into the room.<br>
“You’re going to go fight the Reaver?”<br>
“Yes.”<br>
“No!” Her face drained of colour, her lips almost turning white. “No, you can’t.”<br>
“Mum, we have to.”<br>
“I can’t – what if you…”<br>
“Mum.”<br>
I stood up, facing her. Arianne remained on the floor, watching me carefully.<br>
“We don’t know how to fight it. We can’t run, can’t hide, can’t pretend it could be the end ’cause it might. And we can’t wait for it to come to us. We’re going to go to it. This is the big one, the worst. The one we may just die fighting. But there’s one thing that will stop it, that’s more powerful than it: us. Mum, I don’t want to do this. I’m sixteen. I don’t want to die. But if Arianne and I win we won’t die for a long time yet.”<br>
Arianne stood beside me. “On top of that, we do this for you. We do this…we do this for Dad.”<br>
Mum had started to cry halfway through all this. And when Arianne said ‘Dad’ there was no stopping her. She opened her arms and, feeling like little kids, we went to her. She held us tight for ages.<br>
“I’m scared,” she whispered. “I’m scared you’re going to leave and you’re never going to come home again.”<br>
“Always going to try.”<br>
Arianne’s voice was muffled. She found my hand and gripped it. I found new strength in that gesture.<br>
“We’re always going to try.”<br>
